Joplin Schools is pleased to announce that Mrs. Heather Van Otterloo, South Middle School, has been selected as one of only 98 teachers for a National History Day (NHD) summer professional development program.

The new course highlights and explores digital resources available at the Library of Congress to develop and support historical argumentation. This course is a feature of NHD’s membership in the Library of Congress’s Teaching with Primary Sources (TPS) Consortium.

As one of the selected teachers, Heather receives free tuition,
graduate credits, and materials for the online program.

Please help us congratulate Heather on being selected!

post_text:
Joplin Schools 2020 fall re-entry plan was approved by the board tonight and is available on the District website. In addition, the Board approved moving the start date back to August 24th.

We encourage parents to review the information in the re-entry plan so they are fully informed about the District’s intent to re-enter on August 24th. Should a parent choose the full virtual option, they should complete the online virtual pre-enrollment form by the end of the day August 6th.

It's important to note that current Joplin students that don’t choose virtual will be placed on an in-class roster. If your student is new to the district they must enroll with their homeschool before getting placed on a virtual or in-person roster. Any commitment to elect virtual is for a full semester.

http://www.joplinschools.org/district/c_o_v_i_d-19_information

post_text:
Joplin Schools received confirmation today, June 27th, that one of our summer school students at Stapleton Elementary tested positive for COVID-19. Out of an abundance of caution, all families of students that had contact with the positive student have been notified. If you were not contacted your child was not exposed.

Meanwhile, the district is doing a deep clean of the school, classrooms, and closing the affected classroom while we continue to work closely with the health department. Furthermore, we are in constant communication and in full cooperation with the health department as we follow their guidance. Thank you for your patience and understanding. Classes will resume Monday.

Meanwhile, the district is doing a deep clean of the school, classrooms, and closing the affected classroom while we continue to work closely with the health department. Furthermore, we are in constant communication and in full cooperation with the health department as we follow their guidance. Thank you for your patience and understanding. Classes will resume Monday.

to replace modular units and to provide for additional
classroom space

Please remember to vote on June 2.

post_text:
Earlier this year, we shared with you the reasoning behind the Joplin Schools no tax Increase bond request. While our world has changed a bit since then, the need for safe and equitable schools for all Joplin students has not. We still believe that this proposal is an appropriate and fiscally responsible next step to meeting this goal.

The bond election that was scheduled in April to improve education facilities was postponed by Missouri election officials until Tuesday, June 2. We need your help in spreading the word and helping remind the Joplin Schools patrons of the important question that will be decided on that date!!! Please watch the video for more details

Between preparing healthy food, adhering to strict nutrition standards, navigating student food allergies, and offering service with a smile, Joplin nutrition professionals have a lot on their plate on a “normal” day. Extended building closures during COVID-19 required our foodservice professionals to quickly be innovative and creative to develop ways to continue feeding Joplin students who rely on school breakfast and lunch each day.

Joplin Schools is asking that parents and students prepare "Thank You" signs and banners to show your appreciation and to honk and wave your sings as you pick up your lunches today. Please let these nutrition professionals know how much they've done for the community during this time!

Joplin Schools Nutritional Services
April 28 at 2:39 PM ·

Has your family experienced a job loss, reduction in hours or some other decrease in income during this time? If so, take a few minutes to complete a 2019-2020 free and reduced meal application. If you are approved, those benefits will carry over through the first 30 days of the 2020-2021 school year, EVEN if your income has returned to normal. This will help ease the burden while we all try to get back on our feet. In addition, an increase in the number of students who qualify for free & reduced meals means an increase in funding for Joplin Schools in other areas besides child nutrition.

Visit www.schoolcafe.com to complete an application.

shared_text:
Bright Futures Joplin
April 23 at 3:41 PM ·

Shelter Insurance Agents presented Bright Futures Joplin a check in the amount of $4,000.00 for the Snack Pack program. Shown (left to right) are Bill Williams, Shelter Insurance, Dale Peterson, Bright Futures Joplin, Joy Long, Shelter Insurance , Spencer Layne, Shelter Insurance. Kerry Williams also participated, but was unable to attend.

While maintaining proper social distancing, Bill told us about how Shelter Insurance cares for and gives back to the communities the agents live in. He said that the Shelter Insurance Foundation made this gift possible and the local agents are glad to see it invested in the well being of the children of the Joplin Community. Bill also shared about the Companies return of premium to their customers because of everybody driving less during the stay at home order. They also talked about sharing in the scholarship program that Shelter Insurance Sponsors.

What a great group of people who care for their community!

Bright Futures Joplin is so thankful to be the recipient of this generous donation!

Joplin Schools Nutritional Services
April 14 at 7:43 PM ·

***IMPORTANT MEAL CHANGE INFORMATION***

Beginning April 20th we will be moving our meal service to Monday, Wednesday and Friday pickups from 11 am to noon. Monday and Wednesday's pickup will contain breakfast and lunch for two days, while Friday's pickup will contain three. This change will help to protect both our community and our staff by reducing contact time. We are also including an updated bus schedule (effective April 15th). If you have any questions, please feel free to send us a private message or call us at 625-5315. Thank you for allowing us to serve you during this difficult time!

As many of you know instructional days have been waived for the next two weeks in the state of Missouri. While many resources are being shared, Joplin Schools would like to help provide as much structure to your new normal. Please visit the link below for grades K-8 to access learning opportunities as the district begins long term planning. The high school will continue to use Canvas to access lessons and turn in assignments.
https://drive.google.com/file/d/1GjYKIlugeNHk2_RNL7uH6SMcq63gdcHA/view?usp=sharing
A phone survey will also be conducted next week to better understand device and internet needs. After reviewing the survey results the district will also help make sure hard copy packets are available for students without digital access. Please expect educators to be reaching out to you in the coming days.

We want to remind you to vote on April 7. If you need information regarding the issue the District has on the ballot, you may find it at http://www.joplinschools.org/bond2020. We want to assure you that we have the health of our students and community as a whole as our primary concern during this difficult time. We have included the below information regarding voting via absentee ballot. Absentee Ballot voting will allow you to participate in the democratic election process even if you do not wish to expose yourself to the risk of voting at your local polling location on election day.

Instructions for Absentee Voting:

https://www.sos.mo.gov/elections/goVoteMissouri/howtovote#Absentee

Finding contact information for local election authority:

https://www.sos.mo.gov/elections/govotemissouri/localelectionauthority

Did you know that the average Joplin School District elementary student/teacher ratios per classroom are consistently below the Missouri State Standard Guidelines across all grade levels?

The addition of adequate classroom square footage for Columbia and West Central Elementary students (at a new facility) does not mean the District will be exceeding state standards or District averages. Our goal is safety, equitable learning spaces, and the balanced deployment of resources across the District for ALL Joplin students.

Did you know that since 2013, the District has maintained a debt service of $0.91 per $100 of the assessed property value? That equates to about $170 per year in property taxes for a $100,000 house.

The passage of the bond on April 7, 2020, will not increase the tax rate but would continue a Debt Service Levy no greater than the current levy an additional seven years from 2033 to 2040.

Just a reminder that the Community Safe Rooms are available to the community during a Tornado Warning, and/or when the tornado sirens have sounded. Stay safe this evening!

December 5, 2019 at 9:28 PM ·

Mr. Douglas’ and Stanley’s classes took home a lot of awards at the MSSU Media Showcase Awards today.
Here’s what we won.

Passion for Video Award honoring Will Norton -
1st Place-Samantha Walker

Documentary-
1st Place-"Mexico Documentary"- Nathan Goswick

Comedy-
1st Place-"Jack Attack"-Jack Carey

Sports Pkg-
1st Place-“Undefeated Joplin Football”-Jack Carey

Animation-
1st Place- “Ballad of the Lady”-Nathan Goswick
3rd Place- “Colors” Paige Pritchard

Five Second Video
3rd Place-"Fighting with Force"- Nathan Goswick, Savannah Hubbard
2nd Place “Boys Be Gone” Justice Miller, Hailey Russell, Logan Earl, Bailey Niess. These are four of our Carl Junction sending school students.

Music Video
3rd Place-“Flashlight"-Cora Wesley, Jae Gubera, Nathan Goswick,

Drama-
2nd place "5 Aces”-
Nathan Goswick, Julian Garrett, David Green a sending school student from McCauley.

There were 300 entries this year and we competed against 13 schools including Springfield, Webb City and Southeast Kansas.

Folks are here for tickets there’s still time to get yours! #GoEagles

PRE-SALE STATE CHAMPIONSHIP TICKETS AVAILABLE

Tickets for the MSHSAA Class 6 State Football Championship game between Joplin and De Smet on Saturday, November 30th in Columbia will be available to the community on Wednesday, November 27 from 8:00 to 12:00 at Kaminsky Gym.

Please park in the main lot in front of JHS and enter the North doors of the gymnasium. These tickets are not discounted and are $10.00 each. Cash and check ONLY, no credit cards will be accepted. Please make your checks out to Joplin Schools. All seating for the game will be general admissions.

Tickets are on a first-come-first-serve basis while supplies last!
